  "summary": "While cleaning up broken porcelain, Mrs. Rimsay reflects on the upcoming return of her two energetic children, Bill and Ted, to school after their five-week holiday. Her thoughts are interrupted when Bill informs her that a detective has arrived to discuss a murder that occurred the previous day at the home of Miss Pembroke, a blind woman who works at Allenberg College.\n\nDetective Hakast arrives at the house accompanied by an assistant who takes notes. After Hakast dismisses the children to allow for a private conversation, Mrs. Rimsay denies having any knowledge of the incident at number 19 or regarding the neighbors on New Moon Street. Hakast asks if she was home between 12:30 and 3:00 p.m. the previous day; she confirms she was home during that time, though she left before 3:00 p.m. to take the children to the cinema. Hakast shows her a photograph of the victim, Mr. R. H. Corey, but she does not recognize him.\n\nThe detective notes that the children's gardens are adjacent to the neighbors' and expresses interest in speaking with them, suggesting that children often notice details that adults miss. This leads to a discussion regarding Mrs. Blackham at number 20 and her fourteen cats. Before departing, the man taking notes suggests that Mrs. Rimsay hire an au pair to assist with her household chores.",
